    Why Use Optional?
Traditionally, null values in Java have led to countless NullPointerExceptions,
often in places where the absence of a value wasn't clearly indicated.
Optional makes it explicit when a value might be missing, promoting better readability and safer code.
            Best Practices
1. Use Optional for return types-not fields or parameters.
2. Prefer Optional.empty() over null
3. Use ofNullable() when the value might be null
4. Throw exceptions intentionally with orElseThrow(), You can even use orElseThrow() without arguments in Java 10+


